### Task
Implement TypeScript utility types to create a deeply partial and deeply readonly version of a type.

### Solution
```typescript
// Built-in Partial only works one level deep
type DeepPartial<T> = T extends object
  ? { [K in keyof T]?: DeepPartial<T[K]> }
  : T;

// Built-in Readonly only works one level deep
type DeepReadonly<T> = T extends (infer U)[]
  ? ReadonlyArray<DeepReadonly<U>>
  : T extends object
  ? { readonly [K in keyof T]: DeepReadonly<T[K]> }
  : T;

interface Config {
  server: { host: string; port: number };
  db:     { url: string; maxConnections: number };
}

// Patch only the fields you want to override
function patchConfig(base: Config, patch: DeepPartial<Config>): Config {
  return { ...base, ...patch, server: { ...base.server, ...patch.server },
                              db:     { ...base.db,     ...patch.db     } };
}

// Immutable config object — all properties recursively locked
const frozenConfig: DeepReadonly<Config> = {
  server: { host: 'localhost', port: 8080 },
  db:     { url: 'postgres://...', maxConnections: 10 },
};
// frozenConfig.server.port = 9090; // TS Error: Cannot assign to 'port'
```
Conditional types enable recursive mapped types. The Array branch must be handled separately to produce `ReadonlyArray` rather than a mapped-object type. These patterns ship in TypeScript utility libraries (ts-essentials, type-fest) but are worth knowing from first principles.

### Task
Write a TypeScript generic `Result<T, E>` type (Rust-style error handling) with helper functions.

### Solution
```typescript
type Ok<T>  = { ok: true;  value: T };
type Err<E> = { ok: false; error: E };
type Result<T, E = Error> = Ok<T> | Err<E>;

const Ok  = <T>(value: T): Ok<T>   => ({ ok: true,  value });
const Err = <E>(error: E): Err<E>  => ({ ok: false, error });

function mapResult<T, U, E>(
  result: Result<T, E>,
  fn: (value: T) => U
): Result<U, E> {
  return result.ok ? Ok(fn(result.value)) : result;
}

// Usage: no try/catch, explicit error handling
async function parseJSON<T>(text: string): Promise<Result<T, string>> {
  try {
    return Ok(JSON.parse(text) as T);
  } catch (e) {
    return Err(`JSON parse failed: ${(e as Error).message}`);
  }
}

const result = await parseJSON<{ id: number }>('{"id":1}');
if (result.ok) {
  console.log(result.value.id); // TypeScript knows this is { id: number }
} else {
  console.error(result.error);  // TypeScript knows this is string
}
```
The discriminated union on `ok` lets TypeScript narrow the type in each branch — accessing `.value` inside `if (result.ok)` is fully type-safe with no casting. This eliminates uncaught exceptions for expected failure modes.

### Task
Implement TypeScript decorators for logging method calls and measuring execution time.

### Solution
```typescript
// tsconfig: experimentalDecorators: true

function log(target: any, key: string, descriptor: PropertyDescriptor) {
  const original = descriptor.value;
  descriptor.value = function (...args: unknown[]) {
    console.log(`[${key}] called with:`, args);
    const result = original.apply(this, args);
    console.log(`[${key}] returned:`, result);
    return result;
  };
  return descriptor;
}

function measure(target: any, key: string, descriptor: PropertyDescriptor) {
  const original = descriptor.value;
  descriptor.value = async function (...args: unknown[]) {
    const start = performance.now();
    const result = await original.apply(this, args);
    console.log(`[${key}] took ${(performance.now() - start).toFixed(2)}ms`);
    return result;
  };
  return descriptor;
}

class UserService {
  @log
  getUser(id: number) {
    return { id, name: 'Alice' };
  }

  @measure
  async fetchFromDB(query: string) {
    return db.query(query);
  }
}
```
Method decorators receive (target, propertyKey, descriptor) and modify the descriptor's `value` to wrap the original. Multiple decorators compose bottom-up — `@measure @log method` runs log first, then measure wraps the logged method.

### Task
Create TypeScript type-safe event emitter using mapped types and template literal types.

### Solution
```typescript
type EventMap = {
  'user:login':  { userId: string; timestamp: number };
  'user:logout': { userId: string };
  'post:create': { postId: string; title: string };
  'error':       Error;
};

class TypedEmitter<T extends Record<string, unknown>> {
  private listeners = new Map<keyof T, Set<(data: any) => void>>();

  on<K extends keyof T>(event: K, listener: (data: T[K]) => void): this {
    if (!this.listeners.has(event)) this.listeners.set(event, new Set());
    this.listeners.get(event)!.add(listener);
    return this;
  }

  off<K extends keyof T>(event: K, listener: (data: T[K]) => void): this {
    this.listeners.get(event)?.delete(listener);
    return this;
  }

  emit<K extends keyof T>(event: K, data: T[K]): void {
    this.listeners.get(event)?.forEach(fn => fn(data));
  }
}

const bus = new TypedEmitter<EventMap>();

// Fully type-safe — TypeScript enforces payload shape per event
bus.on('user:login', ({ userId, timestamp }) => console.log(userId, timestamp));
bus.emit('user:login', { userId: 'u1', timestamp: Date.now() });
// bus.emit('user:login', { userId: 'u1' }); // TS Error: missing 'timestamp'
```
Indexing `T[K]` with `K extends keyof T` gives TypeScript full knowledge of the event payload type for each specific event key. This pattern eliminates the runtime cast nightmare of untyped event systems.

### Task
Write TypeScript generics for a type-safe `pick` and `omit` function (like Lodash).

### Solution
```typescript
// Type-level implementations (already in TS as Pick<T,K> and Omit<T,K>)
// Runtime implementations with full type safety:

function pick<T extends object, K extends keyof T>(
  obj: T,
  keys: K[]
): Pick<T, K> {
  return keys.reduce((acc, key) => {
    if (key in obj) acc[key] = obj[key];
    return acc;
  }, {} as Pick<T, K>);
}

function omit<T extends object, K extends keyof T>(
  obj: T,
  keys: K[]
): Omit<T, K> {
  const keySet = new Set(keys as string[]);
  return Object.fromEntries(
    Object.entries(obj).filter(([k]) => !keySet.has(k))
  ) as Omit<T, K>;
}

interface User { id: number; name: string; email: string; password: string; }
const user: User = { id: 1, name: 'Alice', email: 'a@b.com', password: 'hash' };

const public_  = omit(user, ['password']);         // { id, name, email }
const nameOnly = pick(user, ['id', 'name']);        // { id, name }

// TypeScript knows the exact shape:
// public_.email  ✅   public_.password  ❌ (doesn't exist on Omit<User,'password'>)
```
The `K extends keyof T` constraint ensures you can only pick/omit keys that actually exist on the object — typos are compile errors. The return types `Pick<T,K>` and `Omit<T,K>` are TypeScript built-in conditional mapped types.

### Task
Implement a TypeScript class with private fields, getters, and a static factory method.

### Solution
```typescript
class Money {
  readonly #amount: number;   // Private field (native, not TypeScript-only)
  readonly #currency: string;

  private constructor(amount: number, currency: string) {
    if (amount < 0) throw new RangeError('Amount cannot be negative');
    if (!currency.match(/^[A-Z]{3}$/)) throw new TypeError('Invalid currency code');
    this.#amount   = Math.round(amount * 100) / 100; // normalise to 2dp
    this.#currency = currency;
  }

  // Static factory — validates before constructing
  static of(amount: number, currency: string): Money {
    return new Money(amount, currency);
  }

  get amount():   number { return this.#amount; }
  get currency(): string { return this.#currency; }

  add(other: Money): Money {
    if (other.#currency !== this.#currency) throw new Error('Currency mismatch');
    return new Money(this.#amount + other.#amount, this.#currency);
  }

  toString(): string {
    return `${this.#currency} ${this.#amount.toFixed(2)}`;
  }
}

const price   = Money.of(19.99, 'USD');
const tax     = Money.of(1.60,  'USD');
const total   = price.add(tax);
console.log(total.toString()); // USD 21.59
```
Private class fields (`#`) are truly private at the JS level — unlike TypeScript's `private` keyword which is compile-time only and accessible at runtime. The static factory pattern centralises validation and makes the constructor private to prevent invalid construction.

### Task
Write TypeScript conditional types to extract the resolved type from a Promise.

### Solution
```typescript
// Unwrap a promise type one level (built-in: Awaited<T>)
type Unwrap<T> = T extends Promise<infer U> ? U : T;

// Deeply unwrap nested promises
type DeepUnwrap<T> = T extends Promise<infer U> ? DeepUnwrap<U> : T;

// Extract return type of async function
type AsyncReturnType<T extends (...args: any) => Promise<any>>
  = T extends (...args: any) => Promise<infer R> ? R : never;

// Practical examples:
async function fetchUser(): Promise<{ id: number; name: string }> {
  return fetch('/api/user').then(r => r.json());
}

type UserShape = AsyncReturnType<typeof fetchUser>;
// → { id: number; name: string }

type NestedUnwrapped = DeepUnwrap<Promise<Promise<Promise<number>>>>;
// → number

// Conditional mapped type: make all Promise values into their resolved types
type ResolveAll<T> = { [K in keyof T]: Awaited<T[K]> };

type ApiShape  = { user: Promise<User>; posts: Promise<Post[]> };
type Resolved  = ResolveAll<ApiShape>;
// → { user: User; posts: Post[] }
```
The `infer` keyword within conditional types creates a type variable that TypeScript fills during pattern matching. `T extends Promise<infer U>` extracts the generic argument of any Promise type. TypeScript 4.5+ ships `Awaited<T>` as a built-in.

### Task
Implement TypeScript `satisfies` operator to validate object literal types without widening.

### Solution
```typescript
type ThemeColors = {
